  <h2>1. Smoke Is Coming Back Into the Room</h2>

  <p><strong>This is the most dangerous sign — stop using the fire immediately.</strong> When smoke rolls back into the living room instead of going up the chimney, something is blocking the airflow. That could be a bird's nest, heavy creosote buildup, a collapsed flue section, or simply a chimney too dirty to draw properly.</p>

  <p>Carbon monoxide from a poorly venting fire is colourless, odourless and dangerous. Don't light it again until the chimney has been swept and inspected.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>⚠️ Smoke in the room = stop using the fireplace now. This is a carbon monoxide risk, not just an inconvenience.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>2. The Fire Burns Sluggishly or Won't Stay Lit</h2>

  <p>A clean chimney creates a strong updraft that pulls air into the firebox and keeps the fire burning hot. <strong>When the flue is narrowed by creosote, that draft weakens — fires become hard to start, keep dying down, and need constant attention.</strong></p>

  <p>If you're going through twice the kindling you used to, or the fire burns flat and unenthusiastically despite good wood — the flue is the problem, not the wood.</p>

