  <h2>3. There's a Persistent Burnt Smell When the Fire Isn't On</h2>

  <p>A lingering smoky or oily smell — especially on humid days or after rain — is creosote off-gassing from your flue. <strong>If your living room smells like a campfire in January when the fire hasn't been used since August, that's your chimney telling you it needs cleaning.</strong></p>

  <p>In older homes with cracked flue liners, the smell can also indicate combustion gases seeping into wall cavities — which needs urgent attention.</p>

  <h2>4. Heavy Black Soot Around the Firebox Opening</h2>

  <p>Some soot inside the firebox is normal. <strong>Black staining on the wall, mantel or surround around the fireplace opening is not.</strong> It means smoke has been spilling out into the room rather than venting up the chimney — even if you haven't noticed it.</p>

  <p>Creosote-laden smoke leaving deposits around the opening is a clear sign of restricted airflow. The flue needs to be cleaned.</p>

