  <h2>5. It's Been More Than 12 Months Since the Last Clean</h2>

  <p><strong>This is the one most people ignore — and the one that causes the most chimney fires.</strong> Even if your fire seems to draw fine and you haven't noticed anything unusual, a chimney used regularly through a Melbourne winter has accumulated enough creosote to warrant annual cleaning.</p>

  <p>Creosote builds in layers. In its early stages it's light and brushes off easily. Leave it for two or three years and it hardens into a glassy, rock-hard coating that's far more dangerous and far harder to remove. Catching it at the annual clean is infinitely easier than dealing with Stage 3 buildup — or a chimney fire.</p>

